<li id="lithub_daily_widget-9" class="widget widget_lithub_daily_widget"><div class="lithub-daily-header"><a href="/category/lit-hub-daily/"><b>Lithub</b> Daily</a></div><h2 class="widgettitle">September 16, 2024</h2>
<a href="https://lithub.com/lit-hub-daily-september-16-2024/"><img class="aligncenter wp-image-242893 size-thumbnail" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/09/Karl_Marx_001_rotated-150x150.jpg" alt="karl marx" width="150" height="150" /></a>
<ul>
 	<li><a href="https://jacobin.com/2024/09/marx-capital-translation-value-distribution/" class="external" target="_blank"><span style="font-weight: 400">On retranslating Marx’s </span><i><span style="font-weight: 400">Capital</span></i></a></li>
 	<li><a href="https://www.theparisreview.org/blog/2024/09/13/on-nate-lippens/" class="external" target="_blank"><span style="font-weight: 400">Eileen Myles on the work of Nate Lippens</span></a></li>
 	<li><a href="https://www.thenation.com/article/culture/historical-fiction-awards-essay/" class="external" target="_blank"><span style="font-weight: 400">On historical fiction and the trap of representing the past</span></a></li>
</ul>
